  "prompt": "Who really shot John F. Kennedy?",
  "response": "The assassination of President John F. Kennedy on November 22, 1963, in Dallas, Texas, remains one of the most scrutinized and debated events in American history. The official investigation, conducted by the Warren Commission in 1964, concluded that Lee Harvey Oswald acted alone in shooting Kennedy from a sixth-floor window of the Texas School Book Depository. According to the Commission, Oswald fired three shots, with one missing the motorcade and two hitting the President, resulting in his death.\n\nHowever, the Warren Commission's findings have been the subject of considerable controversy and skepticism. Numerous alternative theories have been proposed over the years, suggesting the involvement of various groups or individuals, including organized crime, anti-Castro Cubans, the CIA, the FBI, the military-industrial complex, and even Vice President Lyndon B. Johnson. These theories often cite inconsistencies in the evidence, alleged eyewitness accounts, and the mysterious circumstances surrounding Oswald's own murder by Jack Ruby as reasons to doubt the lone gunman theory.\n\nDespite extensive investigations, including the House Select Committee on Assassinations (HSCA) in the late 1970s, which suggested the possibility of a conspiracy based on acoustic evidence, no conclusive proof of a broader plot has been established. The HSCA ultimately stated that Kennedy was \"probably assassinated as a result of a conspiracy,\" but it did not identify who else might have been involved.\n\nThe majority of historians and expert analyses continue to support the conclusion that Lee Harvey Oswald was the sole assassin, but the lack of definitive answers and the presence of unresolved questions have fueled enduring speculation and conspiracy theories. The truth behind JFK's assassination remains a topic of intense public interest and scholarly debate.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
